isi

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict isi with group and time_point (formula: isi ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.53) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.23. The model’s intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.53 (S.E. = 0.27, p < .001, 95% CI [13.00, 14.06]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.13, S.E. = 0.38, p = 0.736, 95% CI [-0.87, 0.62]; Std. beta = -0.03, 95% CI [-0.21, 0.15])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.50, S.E. = 0.37, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.23, -1.77]; Std. beta = -0.61, 95% CI [-0.79, -0.43])
  • The effect of time point [3rd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.61, S.E. = 1.21, p = 0.613, 95% CI [-2.99, 1.76]; Std. beta = -0.15, 95% CI [-0.73, 0.43])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.73, S.E. = 0.56, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.82, -1.63]; Std. beta = -0.66, 95% CI [-0.93, -0.40])
  • The interaction effect of time point [3rd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -4.75, S.E. = 1.62, p = 0.003, 95% CI [-7.93, -1.57]; Std. beta = -1.15, 95% CI [-1.93, -0.38])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
